ich layer each value came from.\n- `kref fav add \u003cname\u003e \u003cid\u003e [--shared]` / `kref fav rm \u003cname\u003e [--shared]` /\n  `kref fav ls [--user|--shared]` — cobra alias `alt` on `fav`. Default target\n  is the user layer; `--shared` targets the entry and requires it to already\n  exist (create it with `config init --shared`). `add` validates the name\n  constraint (and the id shape) and lints before saving.\n\n## Lint-before-save (write-path invariant)\n\nNot a command — a rule every write path obeys. `edit`, `migrate`, `set`\n(if ever added), and `fav add` validate before persisting; `check` is the same\nlinter read-only. Lint = schema + semantic validation:\n\n- YAML parses; `version` present and an int;\n- only known keys; each value the correct type (`warn_unscanned` bool,\n  `favorites` a name-\u003eid map, `trusted_keys` a list of known key names);\n- every favorite name satisfies the constraints above;\n- `trusted_keys` appears only in the user file (a config entry carrying it is a\n  lint warning + the key is dropped).\n\nSecret-scanning is orthogonal and already guards entry bodies; the user file is\nlocal and owned, so lint here is schema/semantic only.\n\n## Libraries\n\n- `gopkg.in/yaml.v3` — already a direct dep; `yaml.Node` for comment-aware\n  template rewrites during migration.\n- Migrations: hand-rolled compiled-in chain. No FOSS library fits config-file\n  (as opposed to database) schema migration; golang-migrate/goose/gormigrate\n  are all DB tools. Precedent copied: golangci-lint's own config migrate.\n- No viper. If uniform flag\u003eenv\u003econfig\u003edefault precedence ever becomes a real\n  requirement, viper can later Unmarshal into the same struct without rework.\n\n## Testing\n\nUnit:\n\n- loader layering (user overrides project per-key; favorites deep-merge, user\n  wins);\n- trust filtering (entry-sourced non-trusted keys dropped+warned; `trusted_keys`\n  from an entry ignored);\n- favorite-name constraint (accept todo/roadmap/kref.conf-reserved-reject/\n  spec-1; reject beef/cafe/1234/deadbeef/leading-dash/whitespace);\n- resolution folding (favorite resolves; unknown falls through to hex prefix);\n- migration chain (v1-\u003eN transforms; `.bck` written; newer-than-binary refuses\n  write; sparse file takes defaults);\n- lint (each failure mode above rejected).\n\nE2E (Venom):\n\n- `fav add/rm/ls` round-trip + `show \u003cfavorite\u003e` resolves;\n- `config init` / `edit` (non-interactive lint-fail path) / `migrate`;\n- `--shared` creates/updates the entry and syncs; `config` effective view shows\n  source layer;\n- `warn_unscanned: false` silences the ingest \"stored UNSCANNED\" warning.\n\nTests set `GIT_CONFIG_GLOBAL=/dev/null GIT_CONFIG_SYSTEM=/dev/null` and\nkref-specific `GIT_AUTHOR_*` / `GIT_COMMITTER_*`, per project test policy.\n"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1783121540,"nonce":"a4BF7dLIoDvHs751b9zJmjSEQRY=","body":"Config + aliases/favorites — consolidated design spec\n\nStatus: APPROVED 2026-07-03 (Trevor + Claude brainstorm). Replaces the empty\ndraft this entry previously held. Pre-release: no back-compat obligations.\n\n## Problem\n\nkref has no user configuration file today (`XDG_CONFIG_HOME` is touched only to\npick a completion-install dir) and no way to name an entry. This spec adds the\nfirst config-loading path and a favorites/alias facility, as one consolidated\nfeature. It also carries the betterleaks warn-silencer promised when\nwarn-not-fail landed.\n\n## Goals\n\n- A two-layer config: a personal user file plus a shared, dogfooded project\n  config that lives as a kref entry (zero working-tree footprint).\n- Favorites == aliases: one mechanism, human name -\u003e entry id, resolvable\n  anywhere an id is accepted.\n- A trust boundary between the local (trusted) file and the syncable\n  (untrusted-by-default) entry, controlled by the user, not hard-coded.\n- Forward evolution: new/renamed/removed keys handled by versioned migrations\n  so users never hand-edit to stay current.\n- Correctness on write: no invalid config is ever persisted (lint-before-save).\n\n## Non-goals (v1)\n\n- `scanners:` key — arrives later with the custom-scanner feature as a v2\n  migration; NOT pre-reserved as a stub. Trust placement already decided\n  (user-only, excluded from `trusted_keys` by omission).\n- Structural 3-way merge of the shared entry — deferred; see Concurrency.\n- `include:` / entry-includes — YAGNI for now (the trust rule that would make\n  entry-includes safe is designed below for when it returns).\n- viper, and env/flag precedence layering — not warranted for one flat file\n  plus one in-memory entry blob; deferrable with zero rework (load into a\n  struct now; viper can Unmarshal into it later if that need appears).\n- `kref config get/set` scalar CRUD — `edit` covers the one routine scalar and\n  keeps the root-of-trust key off any scriptable path.\n\n## Architecture — two layers\n\nPrecedence, highest wins, per-key:\n\n1. user file  `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/kref/config.yaml`  (trusted, local)\n2. project entry  `kind:config`, reserved alias `kref.conf`  (shared, syncable)\n\n- The project entry is discovered BY KIND (the one `kind:config` entry per\n  tier), so `kref.conf` resolves without needing the favorites table — this\n  breaks the bootstrap cycle (favorites are defined inside the config, yet the\n  config entry must be found before favorites exist).\n- Scalar keys: user value overrides project value.\n- `favorites:` maps deep-merge by name; on a same-name clash the user layer\n  wins.\n\nLoader pipeline (every command, cheap):\n\n    read user file -\u003e migrate in-memory -\u003e (auto-rewrite file if stale) -\u003e validate\n    discover kind:config entry -\u003e migrate in-memory -\u003e filter through trusted_keys -\u003e validate\n    merge (user over project) -\u003e effective config\n\nLoad-time validation failure differs by medium: an invalid USER FILE is a hard\nerror (refuse to run; point at `kref config check` and the `.bck` if present) —\na broken personal file must be fixed, not silently ignored. An invalid or\nun-discoverable PROJECT ENTRY degrades to defaults with a warning — a broken\nshared entry must never brick every teammate's commands.\n\nv1 has a SINGLE project config entry, discovered by kind. If more than one\n`kind:config` entry exists (e.g. one per tier), that is a `check` warning\n(ambiguous project config) and the lexically-first id is used. The entry is\ncreated by `kref config init --shared` and lives in one tier; all `--shared`\nwrites target that one entry.\n\n## Trust model\n\nTrust is a property of the SOURCE MEDIUM, not of position:\n\n- Local files (the user file; any future file-include) are fully trusted —\n  you typed the path.\n- kref entries (the project config; any future entry-include) are\n  untrusted-by-default — a teammate may have edited the entry after you\n  aliased it. Every entry-sourced key passes through the user's `trusted_keys`\n  allowlist; keys outside it are dropped with a warning.\n\n`trusted_keys` is the root of trust and therefore has a hard invariant: it may\nONLY be set in the local user file. It is never honored from a config entry,\nnever settable by any command, never influenced by a remote. Otherwise a\nsyncable entry could expand its own privileges.\n\nDefault `trusted_keys: [favorites, warn_unscanned]`. `scanners` is omitted by\ndesign (it names executables that run on ingest; a synced entry must not choose\nwhat runs on your machine). The shipped template documents this omission inline.\n\n## Favorites (== aliases)\n\nData: `favorites: { \u003cname\u003e: \u003cfull-id\u003e, ... }` in either layer.\n\nName constraints (validated at `fav add` and by the linter):\n\n- MUST contain at least one character outside the lowercase-hex set `[0-9a-f]`\n  (so a name can never be a bare hex id-prefix -\u003e namespaces are disjoint -\u003e\n  `Store.Resolve()` needs NO precedence rule).\n- No ASCII whitespace; no leading `-` (would parse as a flag).\n- Reserved: `kref.conf` (the project-config alias) is refused.\n- Recommended charset for the template/help: `[A-Za-z0-9._-]+` intersected\n  with the non-hex rule.\n\nResolution: `Store.Resolve()` gains a favorites lookup — an exact favorite-name\nmatch returns its id; otherwise fall back to today's hex-prefix resolve. Because\nnames are disjoint from hex, order is immaterial and no ambiguity can arise. As\na result a favorite works anywhere an id does: `show`, `diff`, `log`, `update`,\n`label`, `link`, etc.\n\nSurfacing:\n\n- `kref fav ls` lists both layers merged, marking each row's origin\n  (`user` / `shared`) with the target entry's title.\n- `kref show \u003cid\u003e` header gains a `Favorites` row (symmetric with `Labels`)\n  listing any names pointing at that entry; `--json` gains the same.\n\n## Config evolution — versioned migrations\n\n- Top-level `version: \u003cint\u003e`; the binary carries `CurrentConfigVersion`.\n- Migrations are a compiled-in ordered chain of `func(*yaml.Node) *yaml.Node`\n  (single source of truth, same binary-shipped pattern as `agents_md` /\n  `completion`). They may add, rename, remove, or transform keys.\n- Modeled on golangci-lint's own config `migrate` (the closest precedent — a\n  cobra CLI migrating its YAML config across a major version, and already in\n  kref's toolchain):\n  - write a `.bck` backup of the file before rewriting it;\n  - validate before migrating;\n  - regenerate comments from the current template rather than preserve user\n    comments (kref's comments are canonical docs; fresh docs are the desired\n    outcome, and the `.bck` means nothing is lost).\n- Because defaults are compiled in, a sparse or old file is always valid — a\n  missing key takes its default. Migration is about surfacing/adopting new keys\n  WITH their docs, and about renames/removals; it is never required for\n  correctness.\n\nAsymmetric write policy (the two media differ):\n\n- User FILE: reads migrate in-memory AND the file is auto-rewritten in place on\n  load when stale (local, safe, transparent; `.bck` first).\n- Project ENTRY: reads migrate in-memory only. The migrated form is written\n  back ONLY via explicit `kref config migrate` — one authored, syncable change\n  that mints a single new entry version, never silent per-clone churn.\n- A file/entry whose `version:` is NEWER than the binary (user downgraded kref)\n  is a hard stop on writes: warn and refuse to rewrite; operate on the\n  in-memory-usable subset. Never let an old binary downgrade a newer file.\n\n## Concurrency — shared entry\n\nTwo teammates offline each `kref fav add ... --shared`; both push; the\n`kind:config` entry now has two divergent versions.\n\n- v1: the config entry rides the general stale-write CAS planned for all body\n  writes (a separate TODO item). The second writer is told their copy is stale,\n  re-pulls, and re-applies. No config-only merge UI is built.\n- Future: structural 3-way merge of the `favorites:` map (auto-merge disjoint\n  additions; surface only same-name/different-id conflicts). This is the real\n  meaning of the original \"mergetool-style\" note. It is unblocked by, and\n  sequenced after, the cross-stack divergence LOCATOR now recorded on the TODO\n  (kref entry 81be409e4ef8) — you must be able to FIND divergences across the\n  stack before resolving them, not just count them.\n\n## Commands\n\n- `kref config init [--shared] [--tier \u003cname\u003e]` — write the full commented\n  template to the user file (refuse if it exists unless `--force`); `--shared`\n  creates the `kind:config` entry (alias `kref.conf`), defaulting to the sole\n  shared tier when exactly one exists, else `--tier` is required.\n- `kref config edit` — open the user file in `$EDITOR`, creating from template\n  if absent. visudo-style: edit a temp copy, lint on save, re-offer the editor\n  (or discard) on failure; replace the real file only when lint passes.\n- `kref config check` — the linter exposed read-only: report version status\n  (\"file at vN, current vM — run kref config migrate\"), unknown/untrusted keys,\n  favorite-name violations, and betterleaks presence. Honors `--json`.\n- `kref config migrate` — explicit migration; required for the project entry\n  (auto-migration never touches it) and a manual trigger for the file. Lints\n  the migrated output before writing the file (`.bck`) and before minting the\n  entry version.\n- `kref config` (no args) — print the EFFECTIVE merged config; `--json` shows\n  which layer each value came from.\n- `kref fav add \u003cname\u003e \u003cid\u003e [--shared]` / `kref fav rm \u003cname\u003e [--shared]` /\n  `kref fav ls [--user|--shared]` — cobra alias `alt` on `fav`. Default target\n  is the user layer; `--shared` targets the entry and requires it to already\n  exist (create it with `config init --shared`). `add` validates the name\n  constraint (and the id shape) and lints before saving.\n\n## Lint-before-save (write-path invariant)\n\nNot a command — a rule every write path obeys. `edit`, `migrate`, `set`\n(if ever added), and `fav add` validate before persisting; `check` is the same\nlinter read-only. Lint = schema + semantic validation:\n\n- YAML parses; `version` present and an int;\n- only known keys; each value the correct type (`warn_unscanned` bool,\n  `favorites` a name-\u003eid map, `trusted_keys` a list of known key names);\n- every favorite name satisfies the constraints above;\n- `trusted_keys` appears only in the user file (a config entry carrying it is a\n  lint warning + the key is dropped).\n\nSecret-scanning is orthogonal and already guards entry bodies; the user file is\nlocal and owned, so lint here is schema/semantic only.\n\n## Libraries\n\n- `gopkg.in/yaml.v3` — already a direct dep; `yaml.Node` for comment-aware\n  template rewrites during migration.\n- Migrations: hand-rolled compiled-in chain. No FOSS library fits config-file\n  (as opposed to database) schema migration; golang-migrate/goose/gormigrate\n  are all DB tools. Precedent copied: golangci-lint's own config migrate.\n- No viper. If uniform flag\u003eenv\u003econfig\u003edefault precedence ever becomes a real\n  requirement, viper can later Unmarshal into the same struct without rework.\n\n## Testing\n\nUnit:\n\n- loader layering (user overrides project per-key; favorites deep-merge, user\n  wins);\n- trust filtering (entry-sourced non-trusted keys dropped+warned; `trusted_keys`\n  from an entry ignored);\n- favorite-name constraint (accept todo/roadmap/kref.conf-reserved-reject/\n  spec-1; reject beef/cafe/1234/deadbeef/leading-dash/whitespace);\n- resolution folding (favorite resolves; unknown falls through to hex prefix);\n- migration chain (v1-\u003eN transforms; `.bck` written; newer-than-binary refuses\n  write; sparse file takes defaults);\n- lint (each failure mode above rejected).\n\nE2E (Venom):\n\n- `fav add/rm/ls` round-trip + `show \u003cfavorite\u003e` resolves;\n- `config init` / `edit` (non-interactive lint-fail path) / `migrate`;\n- `--shared` creates/updates the entry and syncs; `config` effective view shows\n  source layer;\n- `warn_unscanned: false` silences the ingest \"stored UNSCANNED\" warning.\n\nTests set `GIT_CONFIG_GLOBAL=/dev/null GIT_CONFIG_SYSTEM=/dev/null` and\nkref-specific `GIT_AUTHOR_*` / `GIT_COMMITTER_*`, per project test policy.\n\n## As-built (2026-07-03) — implemented on branch feat/config-favorites (30 commits, NOT merged)\n\nDelivered per this spec; judgment calls and deviations recorded here.\n\n- **Sparse layers via `WarnUnscanned *bool`.** To honor \"user overrides project\n  per-key\", config layers are SPARSE: `Parse` returns only keys present in the\n  bytes (absent → nil/zero), and `Merge` fills defaults from `Default()`. A\n  present user file that omits `warn_unscanned` therefore does NOT clobber a\n  project entry's value. `Template` renders `warn_unscanned`/`favorites` as\n  COMMENTED docs when unset (active only when the layer set them); `config init`\n  writes `InitialUserConfig()` (warn_unscanned unset). `WarnUnscannedOn()`\n  resolves nil→true.\n- **JSON is snake_case** (`config.Config` got `json` tags): `kref config --json`\n  emits `version`/`warn_unscanned`/`favorites`/`trusted_keys`.\n- **Trust filter is airtight.** Entry-sourced config passes through `Filter`,\n  which drops untrusted keys and ALWAYS clears `trusted_keys`; `Merge` takes\n  `trusted_keys` from the user layer only. An entry can never set the root of\n  trust or an untrusted key.\n- **`scanners` is not a v1 key** (arrives as a future v2 migration, as planned).\n- **Favorite-name rule:** reject empty, reserved `kref.conf`, leading `-`,\n  whitespace, and `^[0-9a-f]+$` (pure hex). `kref.conf` resolves to the project\n  config entry by KIND via a special-case in `Store.Resolve` (works before any\n  favorite exists).\n- **`warn_unscanned` gates ONLY the advisory** \"stored UNSCANNED\" warning\n  (ingest summary + `update --file`); the sync-push boundary still fail-closes\n  on a missing scanner regardless. Wired in cmd/kref, unit-tested.\n- **`config edit` writes VERBATIM** (visudo-style: temp copy → $EDITOR → lint →\n  re-offer/discard on failure → verbatim save via `config.WriteBytes`, `.bck`\n  backup). Only migration regenerates from the template.\n- **Newer-than-binary config is a HARD error on `store.Open`** (clear \"upgrade\n  kref\" message), stricter than the spec's \"warn + operate\" nicety. Moot at\n  CurrentVersion=1; revisit if a real downgrade path appears.\n- **`Validate` does not require `version`** on a sparse layer (migration owns\n  version currency); it rejects only a negative version.\n- **Config loads eagerly on every `store.Open`** (`findConfigEntry` scans\n  `kind:config` across tiers). Fine at kref scale; a lazy-load or a cached\n  config-entry id is a future optimization if the per-command scan ever matters.\n- **E2E is ginkgo `-tags e2e`** (the project's convention), NOT venom — 5 new\n  specs in test/e2e/config_favorites_e2e_test.go; full e2e suite green.\n- **Concurrency (shared entry): unchanged from the spec** — rides the future\n  stale-write CAS; no structural merge built. `fav --shared` uses last-write-wins\n  `Store.Update` today.\n"},{"type":11,"timestamp":1783133412,"nonce":"nhGuIMC/h9fRTZjL0XeJifcnlwM=","actor":"Trevor Vaughan","actor_kind":"human","source_path":"","trigger":"retier"}]}